@JamesM:  
Because "turtle" was a slang term for an error, and the typical standard of the time was three errors in a book before one goes back and re-does the typesetting, the idea was that because the printer's mark was two turtles (instead of, say, a dolphin) that "used up" two of the errors, and so it was intended as a claim that there would be only _one_ actual error in the book, at most.

I thought the original post explained this clearly.
